Christina Koch joined NASA's astronaut corps in 2013 and also who led the first all-female spacewalk in 2019. FLORIDA - Absence makes the canine tail wag harder. American astronaut Christina Koch received numerous accolades from her record-breaking, 328-day spaceflight and then a healthy dose of doggy love upon her return home, according a video she posted on social media on Thursday.  The video shows her dog wagging up a storm, peering out the front door with her front paws on the window sill as Koch nears. The dog flips out, even more, when Koch enters the home, greeting her with some serious face-licking. READ: US astronaut returns to Earth after longest mission by woman The astronaut's capsule landed in Kazakhstan on 6 February after her historic trip to the International Space Station, ending a 328-day mission that set the record for the longest stay in space by a woman. Koch, a North Carolina-born engineer who joined NASA's astronaut corps in 2013, also who led the first all-female spacewalk in 2019.